1. Import and explore data

Your experimental data should include at least: response, treatment factors, treatment factor levels, treatments, replications.

Terminology:
- Response (y): measured variables, e.g.yield, height
- Treatment factor (x): controlled variables, e.g.light intensity, N dose
- Treatment factor levels: levels of treatment factor, e.g.low and hgih light intensities; low and high N doses
- Treatments: combinations of factor levels used in the experiment, e.g.low light intensity at low N
- Replications: repetitions of treatments
- Experimental unit: units to which the treatments are (randomly) assigned, e.g.field plot, reactor I
- Measurement units: parts of the experimental unit at which the response is measured, e.g.granules in a reactor

Import data:

library(readxl)
Exp <- read_excel("Data.xlsx")

Explore data:

2. Data manipulation

2.1 Subset data

We only want the results of soils amended with compost:

soil_comp <- Exp[c(7:18),]

Alternatively, we can use the package dplyr to select data:

library(dplyr)
## Warning: package 'dplyr' was built under R version 4.0.5
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
soil_comp <- Exp %>% filter(Amendment_Type == "Compost")

If we want the results of soil amended with high dose of compost:

soil_comp_H <- Exp %>% filter(Amendment_Type == "Compost", Dose == "High")
soil_comp_H <- Exp %>% filter(Amendment_Type == "Compost" & Dose == "High")

# different from
df <- Exp %>% filter(Amendment_Type == "Compost"|Dose == "High")

Note:

Available comparison operators are:
both & and , logical AND
| logical OR
< less than

df_pH <- Exp %>% filter(pH > 8.3)

> greater than
== equal to
<= less than or equal to
>= greater than or equal to
!= NOT equal to (exclamation mark indicates negation)

If we want to exclude the control:

Soil_treated <- Exp %>% filter(Amendment_Type == "Compost"|Amendment_Type == "Biochar")
Soil_treated <- Exp %>% filter(!Amendment_Type == "No")

If we want to select some columns:

pH.1 <- Exp$pH
pH.2 <- Exp[, c(2:5)]
select_columns <- Exp[, c(2,5,7)]

2.2 Order data

pH from low to high:

pH <- order(Exp$pH, decreasing = T)
head(pH) # rank the rows
## [1] 21 26  9 20  5 23
Exp.ordered <- Exp[pH,]

2.3 Merge data

LIMS <- read_excel("IC.xlsx", sheet = "LIMS")
# Remove un-used columns
LIMS <- LIMS[,-c(1,2,4:7,11)]

samples <- read_excel("IC.xlsx", sheet = "Samples")

IC <- merge(samples, LIMS, by="Ordno")
IC$Result <- as.numeric(IC$Result)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
# order based on analyte
IC <- IC[order(IC$Analyte),]

# select based on analyte
nitrate <- IC %>% filter(Analyte == "Nitrate")
nitrite <- IC %>% filter(Analyte == "Nitrite")
phosphate <- IC %>% filter(Analyte == "Phosphate")

2.4 Calculate

phospahte_mean <- phosphate %>% 
  group_by(Treatment) %>%
    summarize(mean_phosphate = mean(Result), sd_phosphate = sd(Result))

Exp$pH_WC <- Exp$pH*Exp$WC

2.5 Save and export data

library("openxlsx")
## Warning: package 'openxlsx' was built under R version 4.0.5
wb <- createWorkbook()
addWorksheet(wb, "nitrate")
addWorksheet(wb, "nitrite")
addWorksheet(wb, "phosphate")
writeData(wb, sheet="nitrate", nitrate)
writeData(wb, sheet="nitrite", nitrite)
writeData(wb, sheet="phosphate", phosphate)
saveWorkbook(wb, "IC_merge.xlsx")

3. Plot data

A very useful package ggplot2 to build your graph step by step with three components: a data set, a coordinate system, and geoms (visual marks that represent data points).
geoms:
- scatter plots (geom_point)
- bar plots (geom_bar)
- box plots (geom_boxplot)
Much more options offered by ggplot2 (ggplot cheat sheet)

Scatter plots

library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 4.0.5
# plot pH

# a data set + coordinate
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) 

# add the third components geom
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point() 

# adjust the aesthetics
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=Dose)) 

# check the types of the column (character, numeric, factor...)
class(Exp$Dose)
## [1] "character"
Exp$Dose <- as.factor(Exp$Dose)
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=Dose)) 

ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=Dose), size=5, alpha=1)

# change color
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=Dose), size=5, alpha=1) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#e76f51","#264653","#e9c46a")) 

# adjust the theme background
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=Dose), size=5, alpha=1) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#e76f51","#264653","#e9c46a"))  +
  theme_classic()

ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=Dose), size=5, alpha=1) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#e76f51","#264653","#e9c46a")) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

Exp$Amendment_Type <- as.factor(Exp$Amendment_Type)
Exp$Amendment_Type <- factor(Exp$Amendment_Type, levels=c("No", "Compost","Biochar"))
# change x,y axis, and size
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=Dose), size=5, alpha=1) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#e76f51","#264653","#e9c46a")) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  labs(y = "pH of the soil", x = element_blank()) +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12),
        axis.title=element_text(size=14,face="bold")) +
  ylim(0,10)

# change legend
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=Dose), alpha=1, size=5) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#e76f51","#264653","#e9c46a")) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  labs(y = "pH of the soil", x = element_blank()) +
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12),
        axis.title=element_text(size=14,face="bold")) +
  theme(legend.position=c(0.1,0.2),
        legend.direction = "vertical",
        legend.title=element_text(size=20), 
        legend.text=element_text(size=9))

# box plots
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH, color=Dose)) + 
  geom_boxplot() 

ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=pH, color=Dose)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(y = "pH of the soil", x = element_blank()) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  theme(legend.position="bottom",
        legend.direction = "horizontal") +
  scale_color_manual(name = "Dose", labels = c("Low", "High", "Nothing applied"),
                    values=c("#e76f51","#264653","#e9c46a"))

# bar plot
ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=AN, fill=Dose)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity")

ggplot(Exp, aes(x=Amendment_Type, y=AN, fill=Dose)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge", width=0.5)

# By default geom_bar() uses stat_count() to plot the frequency of cases at each level of x (some grouping variable)

ggplot(Exp, aes(x=WC, y=pH)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  stat_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

# https://coolors.co/ for color selection and generation

Note:

  • Spaces in commands do NOT matter
  • CAPITALIZATION does matter
  • TRUE and FALSE are logical constants, you can also use abbreviations T and F
  • Both single-quotes and double-quotes symbols are valid
  • args(functionName) will show the arguments for functionName with default values
args(read.table)

Argument matching

  • match on position: read.table(filename.txt, TRUE, )
  • match by name: read.table(file=filename.txt, header=T, sep=)
  • Both argument matching types can: read.table(filename.txt, header=F, sep=)

Missing values

If there are missing values NA:
- NAs will be carried through in computations
- Operations on NA will always return NA as the result

Result <- IC$Result
Result
##  [1] 0.37 0.38 0.37   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA   NA
## [16]   NA   NA   NA 0.33 0.36 0.35 0.32 0.29 0.32 0.40 0.38 0.41
mean(Result)
## [1] NA
mean(Result, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 0.3566667
